'''Govia Thameslink Railway''' ('''GTR''') is the [[train operating company]] that operates the [[Thameslink, Southern and Great Northern]] franchise. They run the [[Thameslink and Great Northern]] services, formerly operated by [[First Capital Connect]]. [[Southern (train operating company)|Southern]] and [[Gatwick Express]] services will join the network in July 2015 and their brand identities will remain.<ref>{{cite news|last=Topham|first=Gwyn|title=FirstGroup loses Thameslink franchise to Go-Ahead joint venture|url=http://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/may/23/firstgroup-loses-thameslink-franchise-go-ahead-joint-venture|accessdate=24 May 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|date=23 May 2014}}</ref> The merger will create the largest franchise in terms of passengers, staff and fleet.<ref>{{cite news|title=New rail franchising deal set to transform passenger services across London and south east|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-rail-franchising-deal-set-to-transform-passenger-services-across-london-and-south-east|accessdate=24 May 2014|newspaper=Department for Transport (DfT)|date=23 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Govia wins Thameslink rail franchise|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-27534731|accessdate=24 May 2014|newspaper=BBC News Online|date=23 May 2014}}</ref> GTR is part of [[Govia]], a joint venture between [[Go-Ahead Group]] (65%) and [[Keolis]] (35%).

==Thameslink and Great Northern services==
[[File:Ely, Class 365 in TSGN livery.JPG|thumb|[[Thameslink and Great Northern|Great Northern]] [[British Rail Class 365|Class 365]] at [[Ely railway station|Ely]]]]
{{main|Thameslink and Great Northern|Thameslink|Great Northern Route}}
Govia Thameslink Railway has operated Thameslink and Great Northern services since 14 September 2014. Thameslink is a 68-station main-line route running {{convert|225|km|abbr=on}} north to south through London from [[Bedford railway station|Bedford]] to [[Brighton railway station|Brighton]], serving both [[London Gatwick Airport]] and [[London Luton Airport]], with a suburban loop serving [[Sutton railway station (London)|Sutton]], [[Mitcham Junction railway station|Mitcham]] and {{stnlink|Wimbledon}} and on weekdays a suburban line via {{rws|Catford}} and {{rws|Bromley South}} to {{rws|Sevenoaks}}. Great Northern is the name of the suburban rail services run on the southern end of Britain's [[East Coast Main Line]] and associated branches. Services operate to or from {{stnlnk|London King's Cross}} and {{stnlnk|Moorgate}} in London. Destinations include {{stnlnk|Hertford North}}, {{stnlnk|Welwyn Garden City}}, {{stnlnk|Stevenage}}, {{stnlnk|Peterborough}}, {{stnlnk|Cambridge}} and {{stnlnk|King's Lynn}}.

==Southern and Gatwick Express services==
[[File:Watford Junction railway station MMB 06 377212.jpg|thumb|[[Southern (train operating company)|Southern]] [[British Rail Class 377|Class 377]] at [[Watford Junction]]]]
{{main|Southern (train operating company)|Gatwick Express}}
The Southern and Gatwick Express brands will join Govia Thameslink Railway in July 2015. Southern routes run from London Victoria and London Bridge through the South London suburbs of [[Battersea]], [[Norbury]], [[Peckham]], [[Sydenham]], [[Crystal Palace, London|Crystal Palace]], [[Norwood, London|Norwood]], [[Croydon]], [[Streatham]], [[Purley, London|Purley]] and [[Sutton, London|Sutton]] to towns surrounding London like [[Caterham]], [[Epsom]] and [[Tadworth]]. Further afield, Southern also serve [[Redhill, Surrey|Redhill]], [[Tonbridge]], [[Uckfield]], [[East Grinstead]], [[Gatwick Airport]], [[Brighton]], [[Ashford, Kent|Ashford (Kent)]], [[Worthing]], [[Hastings]], [[Portsmouth]], [[Eastbourne]], [[Horsham]], [[Southampton]], [[Littlehampton]] and [[Bognor Regis]]. Additionally, Southern run West London route services from [[Milton Keynes]] to [[South Croydon]] via [[Watford]] and {{rws|Clapham Junction}}. Since 2009, Southern has operated the Gatwick Express service running from [[London Victoria station|London Victoria]] to [[Gatwick Airport railway station|Gatwick Airport]].

